I do have a concern.

01:01:26.310 --> 01:01:28.230
And I'm interested
in your insight

01:01:28.230 --> 01:01:32.520
into whether locally green
policies in California

01:01:32.520 --> 01:01:35.040
contribute to it being so
expensive to live there

01:01:35.040 --> 01:01:37.140
that no one can move there.

01:01:37.140 --> 01:01:39.420
So they all move to
Texas, where they're

01:01:39.420 --> 01:01:41.880
forced to run their air
conditioner for nine months out

01:01:41.880 --> 01:01:42.430
of the year.

01:01:42.430 --> 01:01:44.760
To locally green
policies, is there

01:01:44.760 --> 01:01:48.094
a risk that there's a net effect
that they're globally brown?

01:01:48.094 --> 01:01:50.010
- Yeah, so it's a really
interesting question.

01:01:50.010 --> 01:01:53.340
I mean, this is part of this
whole doing a just transition.

01:01:53.340 --> 01:01:57.180
And the story is not the same
in every single neighborhood.

01:01:57.180 --> 01:02:00.360
But the California
data, the data

01:02:00.360 --> 01:02:02.670
from Portugal, the
data from Denmark

01:02:02.670 --> 01:02:08.010
is very strongly indicating that
high residential prices are not

01:02:08.010 --> 01:02:10.470
due to higher cost electricity.

01:02:10.470 --> 01:02:14.610
In fact, California has some of
the most expensive electricity

01:02:14.610 --> 01:02:17.580
in the country but some
of the lowest electricity

01:02:17.580 --> 01:02:19.460
bills in the country.

01:02:19.460 --> 01:02:22.140
And that's largely
because per kilowatt hour

01:02:22.140 --> 01:02:25.700
is more expensive, but by being
very aggressive on efficiency--

01:02:25.700 --> 01:02:28.640
as is true in Florida,
Wisconsin, New York,

01:02:28.640 --> 01:02:30.880
it is not just a
California thing--

01:02:30.880 --> 01:02:33.260
that overall story
has been a plus.

01:02:33.260 --> 01:02:35.570
And that leads me
to one other thing

01:02:35.570 --> 01:02:38.120
that I cut out just because
I obviously ran long.

01:02:38.120 --> 01:02:41.540
And that is that the
data is unequivocal

01:02:41.540 --> 01:02:45.830
that clean energy
technologies generate more

01:02:45.830 --> 01:02:47.810
jobs than the fossil sector.

01:02:47.810 --> 01:02:50.840
Now, that's not because
it is superior in any way.

01:02:50.840 --> 01:02:53.750
That's because if you're
building a new technology

01:02:53.750 --> 01:02:56.780
base and one where you're
not paying for fuel,

01:02:56.780 --> 01:03:00.830
it's not surprising you get
more jobs per dollar or RND

01:03:00.830 --> 01:03:02.206
invested.

01:03:02.206 --> 01:03:03.830
It's that you're
building a new sector.

01:03:03.830 --> 01:03:05.480
But the fact that
you're not putting

01:03:05.480 --> 01:03:08.240
a huge amount of the
money into the fuel

01:03:08.240 --> 01:03:11.720
means that you're investing in
people and companies and IP.

01:03:11.720 --> 01:03:15.110
And so, we have incredibly
diverse data sets

01:03:15.110 --> 01:03:18.020
that show hugely
larger job creation.

01:03:18.020 --> 01:03:22.490
And my worry is that places
like California that have really

01:03:22.490 --> 01:03:25.190
doubled down on
it, where over 40%

01:03:25.190 --> 01:03:28.520
of all US venture
capital in clean tech

01:03:28.520 --> 01:03:31.520
goes through California, are
going to do well in this deal.

01:03:31.520 --> 01:03:34.850
But when-- I won't name
states, Mississippi--

01:03:34.850 --> 01:03:37.760
and others that are not exactly
on the leading edge finally

01:03:37.760 --> 01:03:40.550
decide to go there,
that green jobs dividend

01:03:40.550 --> 01:03:43.530
will been eaten up by
those who went early.

01:03:43.530 --> 01:03:45.620
And so instead of being
a penalty to go early,

01:03:45.620 --> 01:03:46.820
there is a big benefit.

01:03:46.820 --> 01:03:48.780
But this has to
be more inclusive.

01:03:48.780 --> 01:03:52.570
California is less than
1% of global emissions.

01:03:52.570 --> 01:03:56.030
And so green in California
but not spreading the policies

01:03:56.030 --> 01:03:59.150
that we have, the
policies from Bangladesh,

01:03:59.150 --> 01:04:02.300
from Kenya, from Denmark,
from places that are really

01:04:02.300 --> 01:04:04.032
jumped way ahead,
from Morocco, means

01:04:04.032 --> 01:04:05.240
we're not going to get there.

01:04:05.240 --> 01:04:08.540
And so, I think we are
highlighting a key worry.

01:04:08.540 --> 01:04:10.550
But the places that
have acted actually

01:04:10.550 --> 01:04:13.059
have done quite well in
the deal on that basis.

01:04:13.059 --> 01:04:15.350
California is too expensive
for a lot of other reasons.

01:04:15.350 --> 01:04:17.570
That is everyone
chooses to live within--

01:04:17.570 --> 01:04:20.390
myself included-- within
20 miles of the coast.

01:04:20.390 --> 01:04:24.470
And the key residential
hubs are also

01:04:24.470 --> 01:04:26.810
the places for these
booms of new companies.

01:04:26.810 --> 01:04:28.010
Housing prices are crazy.

01:04:28.010 --> 01:04:30.410
We have graduate
students at Berkeley

01:04:30.410 --> 01:04:33.980
on food stamps as a result
of unaffordable housing.

01:04:33.980 --> 01:04:35.870
But it's not due
to clean energy.

01:04:35.870 --> 01:04:38.449
The worry is proper.

01:04:38.449 --> 01:04:39.490
- I just have a question.

01:04:39.490 --> 01:04:41.323
You were talking about
the Clean Power Plan.

01:04:41.323 --> 01:04:43.900
I was wondering what you think
about the Regional Greenhouse

01:04:43.900 --> 01:04:46.540
Gas Initiative as
compared to that.

01:04:46.540 --> 01:04:52.180
- Yeah, so, you guys are
under a program as well.

01:04:52.180 --> 01:04:55.930
The challenge here has
been that while RGGI is now

01:04:55.930 --> 01:04:59.590
improving a fair amount, the
carbon price is very low.

01:04:59.590 --> 01:05:03.160
And the worry is that
if we had started

01:05:03.160 --> 01:05:06.730
this process of launching
carbon prices early on,

01:05:06.730 --> 01:05:09.940
a low price now that ramped
up very slow would be fine.

01:05:09.940 --> 01:05:14.200
And the contrast would be this
new, bipartisan bill introduced

01:05:14.200 --> 01:05:17.890
in the House and Senate is one
that calls for the carbon price

01:05:17.890 --> 01:05:20.890
to start higher than
California's current price,

01:05:20.890 --> 01:05:22.450
which is about $12 a ton.

01:05:22.450 --> 01:05:26.380
Start more like $20 and
go up $10 every year.

01:05:26.380 --> 01:05:28.900
And that reflects
how much we need

01:05:28.900 --> 01:05:31.420
to move more quickly because
we've really delayed.

01:05:31.420 --> 01:05:33.700
And so, you know, RGGI is good.

01:05:33.700 --> 01:05:37.120
The ETS, which has also had
its ups and downs, figuratively

01:05:37.120 --> 01:05:39.440
and literally, is
also a good thing.

01:05:39.440 --> 01:05:42.310
But I think that the
lesson we've learned so far

01:05:42.310 --> 01:05:44.800
is that a carbon
price is critical

01:05:44.800 --> 01:05:46.510
because we need to
have this dialogue

01:05:46.510 --> 01:05:48.880
between financial
metrics and others.

01:05:48.880 --> 01:05:52.090
But the places that have
moved ahead globally

01:05:52.090 --> 01:05:55.090
have not done so relying
on a carbon price.

01:05:55.090 --> 01:05:57.610
It is one arrow in the quiver.

01:05:57.610 --> 01:06:00.490
It's silver buckshot,
as Al Gore likes to say,

01:06:00.490 --> 01:06:02.860
it's not a silver
bullet unless the price

01:06:02.860 --> 01:06:04.960
gets so high for which
the politics may really

01:06:04.960 --> 01:06:05.980
become challenging.

01:06:05.980 --> 01:06:09.110
So it's a neat point.

01:06:09.110 --> 01:06:11.160
- Thanks for coming
and speaking with us.

01:06:11.160 --> 01:06:13.350
A friend of mine,
an economics grad,

01:06:13.350 --> 01:06:17.330
is moved to Brazil to work on
deforestation in the Amazon.

01:06:17.330 --> 01:06:21.020
And I'm hoping to join her and
learn a little more down there.

01:06:21.020 --> 01:06:25.340
So, on a micro level, what are
some strategies that can help

01:06:25.340 --> 01:06:27.380
on the deforestation forefront?

01:06:27.380 --> 01:06:29.855
And on a larger level,
the election of Bolsonaro

01:06:29.855 --> 01:06:32.761
is definitely a very
bad news for the Amazon.

01:06:32.761 --> 01:06:33.260
- Yeah.

01:06:33.260 --> 01:06:36.770
- What can we do on that
larger level other than shake

01:06:36.770 --> 01:06:37.640
our heads?

01:06:37.640 --> 01:06:41.720
- Well, so there is no silver
bullet answer to that question,

01:06:41.720 --> 01:06:42.220
right?

01:06:42.220 --> 01:06:44.750
But I mean it is
interesting that Brazil

01:06:44.750 --> 01:06:49.460
got a huge amount of early, very
positive press for investing

01:06:49.460 --> 01:06:51.410
in sugar cane ethanol.

01:06:51.410 --> 01:06:55.730
And the early sugar
cane was largely

01:06:55.730 --> 01:07:00.560
on land that had been that had
pulled back from former rubber

01:07:00.560 --> 01:07:01.760
production and others.

01:07:01.760 --> 01:07:05.840
But it's become so profitable
that sugar expansion

01:07:05.840 --> 01:07:08.600
and related crops,
digging into the Amazon

01:07:08.600 --> 01:07:10.110
has become a huge issue.

01:07:10.110 --> 01:07:13.010
And so when you look at
that graph I went over

01:07:13.010 --> 01:07:16.700
in terms of the carbon
content of liquid fuels,

01:07:16.700 --> 01:07:17.990
it's just striking.

01:07:17.990 --> 01:07:22.190
If you really do use
bio waste, then there

01:07:22.190 --> 01:07:24.170
is no environmental
penalty you should

01:07:24.170 --> 01:07:26.997
add to that liter of biofuel.

01:07:26.997 --> 01:07:28.580
But if you're cutting
down rainforest,

01:07:28.580 --> 01:07:32.450
it turns out that you would need
to run your ethanol production

01:07:32.450 --> 01:07:35.930
for over 100 years to
pay back the carbon that

01:07:35.930 --> 01:07:38.480
was standing in those
trees in the rainforest.

01:07:38.480 --> 01:07:42.020
And believe me, this is
not a happy conversation.

01:07:42.020 --> 01:07:45.860
So, if everyone in the front row
is a current food farmer that

01:07:45.860 --> 01:07:48.470
decides to go into
biofuels and you decide

01:07:48.470 --> 01:07:50.970
you're only going to
collect [INAUDIBLE] waste,

01:07:50.970 --> 01:07:52.850
and so you have
no carbon penalty.

01:07:52.850 --> 01:07:55.940
But Alyssa here
says, you know, I'm

01:07:55.940 --> 01:08:01.340
going to convert my current
corn production into biofuels.

01:08:01.340 --> 01:08:02.780
I'm going to do it sustainably.

01:08:02.780 --> 01:08:04.720
I'm going to bless it, I'm going
to-- all these /It's is going

01:08:04.720 --> 01:08:05.510
to be great.

01:08:05.510 --> 01:08:10.340
But someone elsewhere says well,
she's no longer producing corn.

01:08:10.340 --> 01:08:11.900
I'm going to get
into that business.

01:08:11.900 --> 01:08:15.710
And increasingly-- that's
in Indonesia, Brazil, Congo,

01:08:15.710 --> 01:08:16.790
Malaysia--

01:08:16.790 --> 01:08:18.830
then you're cutting
into forests that

01:08:18.830 --> 01:08:21.620
had a much better
value as forests then

01:08:21.620 --> 01:08:24.830
as ethanol producers.

01:08:24.830 --> 01:08:29.330
This conversation does
not go well in Brazil.

01:08:29.330 --> 01:08:32.540
And I have-- sort
of my mentor is

01:08:32.540 --> 01:08:34.279
the father of the
Brazilian ethanol

01:08:34.279 --> 01:08:36.050
industry, an amazing figure.

01:08:36.050 --> 01:08:38.870
He was the host of the
Rio Climate Conference.

01:08:38.870 --> 01:08:42.620
And this is an area where
we're on sensitive ground.

01:08:42.620 --> 01:08:45.800
And so finding a way
to lead with the facts

01:08:45.800 --> 01:08:50.279
and the numbers is my physics
tribe way to do things.

01:08:50.279 --> 01:08:52.310
But this is a really
hard conversation.

01:08:52.310 --> 01:08:54.980
And so, working in the area,
what you guys are supposed

01:08:54.980 --> 01:08:56.479
to do is what I recommend.

01:08:56.479 --> 01:08:59.170
But finding a way
to compare the life

01:08:59.170 --> 01:09:01.580
cycle, to cradle
to grave analysis

01:09:01.580 --> 01:09:03.170
is a critical part of it.

01:09:03.170 --> 01:09:07.330
But that is that's
a seed change,

01:09:07.330 --> 01:09:09.270
and so we don't
have a lot of years.

01:09:09.270 --> 01:09:11.020
But that's a critical
part of the process.

01:09:11.020 --> 01:09:13.130
That's hard.

01:09:13.130 --> 01:09:18.200
- My question was
around corporate world.

01:09:18.200 --> 01:09:20.240
When the CDP put
out a report that

01:09:20.240 --> 01:09:24.380
says that 71% of
carbon emissions

01:09:24.380 --> 01:09:26.870
are being generated
by 100 companies,

01:09:26.870 --> 01:09:29.810
and we're talking about
in this sort of countries,

01:09:29.810 --> 01:09:32.420
and governments, and
things, what are you

01:09:32.420 --> 01:09:35.029
or others in your field
doing to help educate

01:09:35.029 --> 01:09:39.080
and these companies transition
away from this carbon emission?

01:09:39.080 --> 01:09:41.750
- So, this is
actually an area where

01:09:41.750 --> 01:09:44.882
my economics colleagues can give
much better answers than I do.

01:09:44.882 --> 01:09:46.340
And this is the
place where I would

01:09:46.340 --> 01:09:49.580
argue that carbon pricing
can have the most value.

01:09:49.580 --> 01:09:52.399
The fact that carbon enters
our economy through us

01:09:52.399 --> 01:09:53.960
through so few spigots--

01:09:53.960 --> 01:09:55.460
you mentioned the
kind of, you know,

01:09:55.460 --> 01:09:57.260
on the order of 100
companies-- that's

01:09:57.260 --> 01:09:59.120
a remarkably small number.

01:09:59.120 --> 01:10:03.610
So arguments to regulate
carbon at the user end

01:10:03.610 --> 01:10:06.440
may be the standard
policymaking tool.

01:10:06.440 --> 01:10:08.990
But doing it upstream
makes much more sense

01:10:08.990 --> 01:10:11.630
in terms of of efficiency,
even if the increased price

01:10:11.630 --> 01:10:13.100
gets passed down.

01:10:13.100 --> 01:10:15.290
The challenge, of
course, is that if you

01:10:15.290 --> 01:10:18.260
increase the price for
production for those companies

01:10:18.260 --> 01:10:21.320
and don't find a way to
give back to low income

01:10:21.320 --> 01:10:23.990
people around the
planet, then your policy

01:10:23.990 --> 01:10:26.240
might be for the
planet but it's not

01:10:26.240 --> 01:10:28.370
part of this just or
equitable transition.

01:10:28.370 --> 01:10:32.600
And so, one of the features
that I'm hoping the dialogue

01:10:32.600 --> 01:10:33.860
around the bill--

01:10:33.860 --> 01:10:35.720
I really like the
bill in many ways

01:10:35.720 --> 01:10:37.550
that's in front of
the House and Senate--

01:10:37.550 --> 01:10:41.720
is to not just rebate
all of the revenues back

01:10:41.720 --> 01:10:43.490
to all Californians equally--

01:10:43.490 --> 01:10:45.320
I said Californians,
sorry about that--

01:10:45.320 --> 01:10:47.480
to all Americans equally.

01:10:47.480 --> 01:10:49.490
But to actually
say no, we're going

01:10:49.490 --> 01:10:53.660
to give back an extra share to
the lowest income Californian.

01:10:53.660 --> 01:10:57.820
So, what I would do is a
hybrid of the Ocasio-Cortez.

01:10:57.820 --> 01:11:01.130
And that would be if you are
within 200% of the poverty

01:11:01.130 --> 01:11:05.390
line, I would give you back
your share but also a share

01:11:05.390 --> 01:11:09.320
taken from the top
0.01%, and use that money

01:11:09.320 --> 01:11:11.830
both to give back to
low income Americans.

01:11:11.830 --> 01:11:14.300
And a part that's
not in the bill,

01:11:14.300 --> 01:11:16.070
there is no provision
to harvest money

01:11:16.070 --> 01:11:18.040
from the bill for research.

01:11:18.040 --> 01:11:21.620
And I would argue if you want
to do this, you give back a lot.

01:11:21.620 --> 01:11:23.870
But you also need
to hold a fund.

01:11:23.870 --> 01:11:27.530
And we've seen this work
President George Bush started

01:11:27.530 --> 01:11:30.890
ARPA-E, the Advanced Research
Projects Agency for Energy,

01:11:30.890 --> 01:11:32.510
modeled after DARPA.

01:11:32.510 --> 01:11:34.460
It's been phenomenally
successful.

01:11:34.460 --> 01:11:36.880
But it's got a budget
of $300 million a year.

01:11:36.880 --> 01:11:38.930
And if you want to make
a dent here, you know,

01:11:38.930 --> 01:11:40.820
we need to at least get
to the level of what

01:11:40.820 --> 01:11:43.030
the US spends on pet
food research, which

01:11:43.030 --> 01:11:44.480
is over a billion dollars.

01:11:44.480 --> 01:11:45.830
And that's just to start, right?

01:11:45.830 --> 01:11:48.320
So, great question.

01:11:48.320 --> 01:11:49.820
- Thank you for coming.

01:11:49.820 --> 01:11:52.570
[APPLAUSE]

